# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: australian-rules-football-in-canada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The **Stanford rugby teams of 1906 to 1917** represented Stanford University as the school's only football program during those years, replacing American football with rugby union.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The school had played American football from 1892 to 1905, but in 1906, concerned with the growing levels of violence in football, Stanford and other universities changed to rugby.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played twelve seasons of rugby, during which it played other college teams, club teams from the United States, Canada, and Australia, as well as the New Zealand national team and Australia national team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] American football in the early 1900s had become increasingly violent; with no forward pass, the ball carrier would be typically pushed and pulled up the field by his own players in massive formations that often resulted in serious injuries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In 1905, 18 deaths, three at the college level, were attributed to football; 159 serious injuries were also reported, 88 at the college level.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Reform was demanded by such voices as U.S.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] President Theodore Roosevelt, who decried the brutality and foul play of the game, and called a meeting of school presidents to discuss the issue.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As a result, before the next season began, new rules were put in place to discourage such play.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The forward pass was also introduced to open up the game and reduce the role of dangerous mass formations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite the planned changes, a number of universities banned the sport for the coming year, including Columbia, NYU, and Northwestern.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Several universities on the West Coast, led by California and Stanford, replaced the sport with rugby.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] At the time, the future of football was very much in doubt and these schools believed that rugby would eventually be adopted nationwide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Other schools that made the switch included Nevada, St.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] However, due to the perception that West Coast football was inferior to the game played on the East Coast anyway, East Coast and Midwest teams shrugged off the loss of the teams and continued playing football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] With no nationwide movement, the available pool of rugby teams to play remained small.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The schools scheduled games against local club teams and reached out to rugby powers in Australia, New Zealand, and especially, due to its proximity, Canada.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The annual Big Game between Stanford and California continued as rugby, with the winner invited by the British Columbia Rugby Union to a tournament in Vancouver over the Christmas holidays, with the winner of that tournament receiving the Cooper Keith Trophy.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In 12 seasons of rugby, Stanford was remarkably successful: the team had three undefeated seasons, three one-loss seasons, and an overall record of 94 wins, 20 losses, and 3 ties for a winning percentage of .816.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] However, after a few years, the school began to feel the isolation of its newly adopted sport, which was not spreading as many had hoped.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Students and alumni began to clamor for a return to football to allow wider intercollegiate competition.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The pressure at rival California was stronger (especially as the school had not been as successful in the Big Game as they had hoped), and in 1915 California returned to football.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As reasons for the change, the school cited football rule changes, the overwhelming desire of students and supporters to play football, interest in playing other East Coast and Midwest schools, and a patriotic desire to play an "American" game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] California's return to football increased the pressure on Stanford to also change back in order to maintain the rivalry.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played its 1915, 1916, and 1917 "Big Games" as rugby against Santa Clara and California's football "Big Game" in those years was against Washington, but both schools desired to restore the old traditions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The onset of World War I gave Stanford an out: in 1918, the Stanford campus was designated as the Students' Army Training Corps headquarters for all of California, Nevada, and Utah, and the commanding officer, Sam M.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Parker, decreed that football was the appropriate athletic activity to train soldiers and rugby was dropped.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] After the war, Stanford resumed its football program and relegated rugby to a minor sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Several Stanford rugby players who played during those years—including Daniel Carroll, Dink Templeton, Morris Kirksey, Erwin Righter, John Patrick, and Charles Doe—went on to win a gold medal for the United States in rugby at the 1920 Summer Olympics.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In its first season of rugby, Stanford retained head football coach James F.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Lanagan had coached the football team for three years, including an undefeated 1905 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] With no experience playing or coaching rugby, Lanagan initially offered his resignation, but Stanford insisted he stay on, so he traveled to Vancouver, British Columbia to study the sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its first five games, including two wins over a visiting club team from Vancouver.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] As winners of the first Big Game against California played as rugby, Stanford competed against Vancouver-area club teams for the Cooper Keith Trophy, losing two games and tying one.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Stanford's second season of rugby, Jimmy Lanagan returned as coach and the team finished 8–4.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford continued its series with Nevada, Vancouver, and Victoria and added games against Bay Area club team the Barbarians and a Los Angeles club called the Castaways.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its second Big Game rugby match, earning a second straight tournament in British Columbia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Lanagan returned for his final year as Stanford's coach and the team finished 12–2, winning not only its third consecutive Big Game, but also going on to win the Cooper Keith Trophy in the end-of-season Vancouver tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford added two games against San Francisco's Olympic Club and played a final game against the Australian national team, the Wallabies.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Following Lanagan's departure, George Presley was named Stanford's new rugby coach.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Presley played one year of rugby under Lanagan in 1906 and had been an assistant coach in 1907 and 1908.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Presley also coached Stanford's baseball team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford won its first eight games—seven by shutout—but then lost Big Game for the first time in seven years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Presley's second year as coach, Stanford was led by Ben Erb and Jim Arrell.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The season was almost identical to the previous year: the team won its first seven games by shutout, and then lost Big Game to undefeated California.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford led in that game 6–0, but did not score again as California won 25–6.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This Big Game is recognized as the first intercollegiate game to feature card stunts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In the 1911 season, Stanford went 10–3 and added USC to the schedule, as the school dropped football in favor of rugby.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In Presley's last year as coach, Stanford finished with a 5–3–1 record, its worst record of the rugby era.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford avoided a fourth straight loss in the Big Game by tying California.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite an outstanding 30–8–1 overall record as coach, coach Presley was 0–3–1 against the Bears.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Brown succeeded George Presley as coach.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Like Presley, Brown had played for and served as an assistant under the previous coach.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford finished with an 8–3 record, including its first Big Game win in five years, led by Danny Carroll, who had won a gold medal in the 1908 Summer Olympics as a member of the Australia national rugby union team and who was now earning a degree in geology from Stanford.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Stanford played its final rugby game against USC, who returned to American football the next year, and suffered two blowout losses to the famed New Zealand All Blacks, who were on a North American tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Brown's second year as coach was the best in Stanford rugby history: the team was undefeated entering the Big Game at California, who was also undefeated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] A record crowd of 26,000 turned out to see Stanford defeat the Bears, 26–8.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This would be the last Big Game for several years as California returned to football for the 1915 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Despite Stanford's success in rugby, the previous year's humiliating defeats to the All Blacks and the switch by rivals USC and California to football intensified the sentiment for Stanford to switch back as well.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] By 1915, there was only one other U.S. college playing intercollegiate rugby: Santa Clara.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The rest of Stanford's schedule was made up of local club and all star teams.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The team played to a scoreless tie with the Olympic Club team to start the season, but recovered to win the rest of the games on the schedule.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] In their last full season of rugby, Stanford won all its games except the "Big Game" against Santa Clara, played for the second year at Ewing Field in San Francisco.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This was Stanford's first loss since 1913.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] Like the two coaches before him, Stanford's new head coach Jim Wylie was a former Stanford player.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] He had also been a member of the New Zealand All Blacks team that had crushed Stanford's team in 1913.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] But with World War I imminent, Stanford played just one game, the "Big Game" against Santa Clara, winning 15–11.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] This was also Stanford rugby's last game as a major sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] The following year, Stanford president Ray Lyman Wilbur canceled all intercollegiate athletic events due to students' enlisting in the military for the war, and due to Stanford's designation as the regional headquarters of the Students' Army Training Corps.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/1906-1917-stanford-rugby-teams] When Stanford reformed a team in 1919, the school returned to American football as its major gridiron sport.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2002-australian-football-international-cup] The **2002 Australian Football International Cup** was the inaugural international Australian rules football tournament held in Melbourne, Australia in 2002.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2002-australian-football-international-cup] 11 nations participated from around the world and the tournament was officiated by the International Australian Football Council.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2002-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won the tournament, finishing undefeated and victorious over Papua New Guinea in the Grand Final on 23 August at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2002-australian-football-international-cup] A 22 player All-International squad was named, however names were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The **2005 Australian Football International Cup** was the second time that the Australian Football International Cup tournament, an international Australian rules football competition was held.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The event was hosted by both Melbourne and Wangaratta, Australia, in 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] 10 nations participated following the late withdrawal of both Nauru and Denmark and the introduction of Spain.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] All sides were scheduled to play 4 games, after which the top 4 sides played off in semi-finals for a berth in the Grand Final decider.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was between Papua New Guinea and New Zealand.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Both sides went through the tournament undefeated.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] It was played as a curtain raiser to an official Australian Football League premiership season match and was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] New Zealand were crowned international champions for the first time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The grand final was replayed on Fox Sports (Australia) and the Fox Footy Channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] The best and fairest medal was awarded to New Zealand's James Bowden.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Like the All-Australian Team in the Australian Football League, a team selected from the best players in the International Cup was selected.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2005-australian-football-international-cup] Team members were unplaced and not allocated to any specific field position.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The **2008 AFL draft** consisted of four opportunities for player acquisitions during the 2008/09 Australian Football League off-season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] These were trade week (held between 6 October and 10 October), the national draft (held on 29 November), the pre-season draft (16 December) and the rookie draft (16 December).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] It was considered to be the last uncompromised draft before the draft concessions given to the Gold Coast and Greater Western Sydney expansion teams restrict the existing AFL clubs' access to the best young players in the future years drafts.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Throughout the year there was much speculation about high-profile players such as Jonathan Brown, Alan Didak and Daniel Kerr being likely to be traded during the AFL's annual trading period, but each re-signed with their clubs before the trading period started.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The main discussions during trade week were the surprise request by Ryan O'Keefe to be traded from Sydney, as well as the destination of young Fremantle ruckman Robert Warnock, both of whom wished to be traded back to their home city of Melbourne.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Other players to request trades include Andrew Lovett, Brent Prismall, Mark Seaby, Farren Ray, Josh Carr and Daniel Harris.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] North Melbourne surprised many early in the week by naming Hamish McIntosh and Corey Jones as players available to trade, with McIntosh later being withdrawn from the offer after a backlash from his manager and club legend Glenn Archer.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Like most years, no trades were completed during the first three days of the trade week and for the first time the AFL was requested to assist by providing a mediator to solve the stand-off between Fremantle and Carlton over the Warnock deal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Carlton had offered its second round selection, #24 overall, but Fremantle wanted its first round selection, the sixth overall.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] On the final day of trade week Warnock was traded.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] 69, in exchange for Carlton's picks 24, 56 and 72.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] In total only six trades were completed, with O'Keefe, Lovett, Seaby, Carr and Harris unable to finalise deals during the week.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The 2008 national draft was held on 29 November.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Melbourne finished the 2008 AFL season in last position and had the first selection in the draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] As both Melbourne and West Coast Eagles won less than 5 games during the season, they were eligible for a priority pick.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] As this was the first year in which they qualified, the priority pick was allocated between the first and second rounds of selections.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Ayce Cordy was the first player selected in the draft as the only father–son selection.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The Western Bulldogs had to use their 1st round selection, #14, to secure him after St Kilda bid their #1st round selection for him.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] His father, Brian, played 124 games for the Bulldogs in the 1980s.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The top two selections were widely tipped to be Jack Watts and Nic Naitanui, with Daniel Rich, Ty Vickery, Stephen Hill, Chris Yarran and Hamish Hartlett to fill the next few selections.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Richmond, the only club to show interest in recruiting Cousins, had one selection in the pre-season draft (because it had only one space left on its senior list).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] The request was similar to one made by and granted to the Essendon Football Club a few years earlier with respect to Adam Ramanauskas, but there were key differences which led to Richmond's request being rejected by the AFL and a majority of rival clubs on 15 December.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Although Richmond had maintained throughout the previous week that it would draft Cousins only if its request to put Polak on the rookie list was granted, they selected Cousins anyway with their only selection in the pre-season draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Josh Carr's return to Port Adelaide was the other major player move.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] Due to the expansion in the number of rookie places available for clubs to use - from the previous maximum of six players to the maximum of eight rookies and veteran listed players combined - the 2009 rookie draft featured more selections than usual.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-afl-draft] A total of 15 players were promoted from their respective clubs' rookie lists to the club's primary lists at the conclusion of the 2008 season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The **2008 Australian Football International Cup** was the third time the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition, has been contested.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] It was scheduled for 2008 (as part of the 150th year celebrations of Australian Football), with 16 nations competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The tournament was hosted by both Melbourne and Warrnambool in Victoria, Australia between 27 August and 6 September, with a single match additionally played in Geelong.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like previous tournaments, the competition was open to men's teams with strict nationality eligibility rules.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The Grand Final was played between New Zealand and Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Papua New Guinea were victorious by 8 points with a goal kicked after the siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Like the Grand Final in previous years, the match was played at the Melbourne Cricket Ground as a curtain raiser to the 2008 AFL Second qualifying Final which attracted a crowd of 76,703 spectators.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However unlike previous tournaments, the final was not televised.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL later indicated that a regional round and semi-finals would be held in Warrnambool.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL indicated that unlike earlier cups, it would likely be split into two divisions, a premier division and development division, with some discussion as to whether the eligibility rules could be loosened for the development division, to enable more countries to participate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Leagues were given the opportunity to nominate which they would prefer, with eight in each division being an initial target.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Ultimately, this idea was dropped, with the sixteen teams being seeded into four pools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In December 2007, it was announced that Melbourne and Warrnambool would co-host the two division event, with Melbourne matches to be played mainly in Royal Park North.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Several potential new sides were announced by the AFL, including an Israeli-Palestine combination supported by the Peres Centre for Peace, China and India.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The USA Women's team announced an intention to send a squad to play against Australia and possibly Papua New Guinea.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Additionally Canada and England announced their intentions to send Under 17s squads.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] As a result, there was speculation over an inaugural women's and under 17 divisions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] However the AFL denied these divisions in favour of a senior men's competition only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In response, and with the Barassi International Australian Football Youth Tournament being cancelled, British and Canadian junior teams had to organise their own tours and matches against Australian schools.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Despite both international teams being in Australia at the same time, they did not play against each other.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The US women's team announced a 2009 tour instead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The AFL confirmed in July 2008 that sixteen nations will compete.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] In addition, there will be friendly matches played between Melbourne-based migrant community teams under the names "Team Africa" and "Team Asia", as well as the Tongan side which was unable to commit to the full tournament.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] Also despite a previous appearance, the Spain Bulls will not be competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] The world team was selected based on player performance in the pool rounds only.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2008-australian-football-international-cup] India, China, the Peace Team and Finland all missed representation in the team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The **2011 Australian Football International Cup** (also known as the **AFL International Cup 2011** or **IC11**) was the fourth edition of the Australian Football International Cup, an international Australian rules football competition run by the Australian Football League (AFL).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] It was contested between 12 and 27 August 2011 by 18 nations, with games played in both Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Two matches were played as curtain raisers to AFL premiership matches, USA vs South Africa at Stadium Australia and the IC Grand Final at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Ireland won its second men's championship, and the inaugural women's championship (Ryan Aslett Cup).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] 17 of these clubs represented single nations, and one (the Peres Team for Peace) represented both Israel and the Palestinian Territories.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The first round of matches was played with modified rules, most significantly the reduction of game length to two-quarters, in the same manner as the 2011 NAB Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, the best two teams from each Group were regrouped into four groups of three teams, based on Win-Draw-Loss performance and Percentage in Round 1, all within a larger group known as Division 1.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would remain in contention for the International Cup title.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining six were regrouped in the same way, into two subgroups of Division 2.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These teams would compete for a secondary prize.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 1 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] Division 2 teams played one match against each team in their respective groups, as well as a single "cross-over" match against a team in the opposite group.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 2, the teams were once again re-seeded based on their performance in the previous round; the teams in Division 1 were seeded in positions 1-12, and the teams in Division 2 in positions 13–18.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] These matches were played at the same time as the final round 2 Division 2 matches; the Division 2 teams did not participate in this round.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] In the opening round of the Women's International Cup, the five teams played each other once, over the course of 10 days.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] At the conclusion of Round 1, Australia, the lowest ranked team in the competition based on points and percentage, was eliminated and finished in 5th place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2011-australian-football-international-cup] The remaining four clubs will compete in the finals.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The **2012 AFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Hawthorn Football Club and the Sydney Swans at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on 29 September 2012.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] It was the 117th annual grand final of the Australian Football League (formerly the Victorian Football League), staged to determine the premiers for the 2012 AFL season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The match, attended by 99,683 spectators, was won by Sydney by 10 points, marking the club's fifth VFL/AFL premiership victory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney's Ryan O'Keefe was awarded the Norm Smith Medal as the best player on the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn entered the 2012 season having been eliminated in the preliminary finals in 2011 by Collingwood.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn's start to the year was average, with a record of 5–4 after nine matches; the team then won its next eight matches by an average of 81 points.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] A narrow loss against Geelong in Round 19 was its only other loss of the season, and Hawthorn finished the regular season on top of the AFL ladder with a win–loss record of 17–5.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn defeated Collingwood in its first qualifying final by 38 points to progress to the preliminary final, then beat Adelaide in a close preliminary final by five points to qualify for the grand final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney entered the 2012 season having been eliminated in the semi-finals by Hawthorn in 2011.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney won its first five matches of the season, before losing three of its next four matches to fall to 6–3; it then won its next nine matches by an average of 46.5 points; this streak took Sydney to the top of the ladder in Round 15, a position that the Swans held for seven weeks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney lost three of its last four matches, including narrow losses to top four teams Hawthorn and Collingwood, to finish third with a record of 16–6.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney led from start to finish and beat Adelaide by 29 points in the qualifying final, then defeated Collingwood for the first time in 12 matches by 26 points in the preliminary final to qualify for the grand final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The two matches between Hawthorn and Sydney were split this season.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney recorded a convincing 37-point victory at Aurora Stadium in Launceston, Tasmania in Round 5, and Hawthorn recorded a narrow 7-point victory at the SCG in Round 22; it was the latter result which saw Hawthorn move ahead of Sydney on the premiership ladder.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn was contesting its first grand final since its victory in 2008, and Sydney its first since being defeated in 2006.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] It was the first time the two clubs had met in a grand final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The match was televised by the Seven Network.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The coverage commentators included Brian Taylor, Matthew Richardson, Cameron Ling, Michael Malthouse, Tom Harley, Luke Darcy and Leigh Matthews.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The network's coverage of the match peaked at 5.084 million viewers as the match neared its conclusion, with Sydney recording 795,000 and Melbourne recording a peak of 1.574 million.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Seven's parent company Seven West Media said the grand final reached "more than 6 million Australians" during the course of coverage.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Following criticism of the performance of Meat Loaf at the 2011 AFL Grand Final, the AFL changed the format of the entertainment to have a small pre-match show, a larger half-time show, and, for the first time, a free concert open to the public at the Melbourne Cricket Ground after the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Tim Rogers, who was featured in the AFL's finals series advertising campaign, and Paul Kelly performed before the game, and Marina Prior performed the national anthem; The Temper Trap performed at half-time on a stage on the arena.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Kelly and The Temper Trap played at the post match concert.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The annual Grand Final Sprint was moved from half time to pre-match to accommodate the new entertainment schedule.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Patrick Dangerfield (Adelaide) won his second consecutive Grand Final Sprint, with Harry Cunningham (Sydney) second and Angus Litherland (Hawthorn) third.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The match was played in dry, gusty conditions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Throughout most of the lead-up to the match, weather forecasts had been predicting heavy rain, with potential hail and thunderstorms for the match, but the worst of these predictions did not eventuate.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Light rain fell during the halftime entertainment, but the weather for the match itself was primarily cloudy but dry with winds at the MCG trending towards the City End.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn won the toss and chose to attack the City End first.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The first minutes of the match saw the ball move back and forth along the ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Within a minute of play, Hawthorn's Lance Franklin had the first set shot on goal but missed to the left.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Two minutes later, after a scramble at Sydney's attacking end, Lewis Jetta had a shot on goal that missed to the right.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] About 5½ minutes in, Hawthorn captain Luke Hodge was forced off the field because of a cut above his right eye.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] This injury would require him to come off the ground several times throughout the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] By six minutes in, Hawthorn pressed an attack at their forward 50 and finally got the first goal of the match from a quick opportunity by Xavier Ellis.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] One minute later, however, Sydney attacked back, and Nick Malceski hooked a shot from near the boundary to even the score.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] For the next 9 minutes, neither side could kick a goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Although Hawthorn pressed an attack and dominated in possession, the result was only 0.4 for them and 0.1 for Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Finally, near the 17th minute, Franklin took a mark on the forward 50 and kicked a goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney tried to respond with a rally of its own but Craig Bird and Lewis Roberts-Thomson both missed to the left; the trending wind was believed to be a factor in both behinds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Afterwards, Hawthorn got some good bounces and responded with two straight goals (by Luke Breust and Jack Gunston) in the 20th minute to take a nineteen-point lead to quarter time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] As much as the first quarter was dominated by Hawthorn, Sydney responded even more convincingly in the second, showing considerable improvement in tackling pressure and clearances, denying Hawthorn many opportunities despite plenty of time in the forward 50.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] At the 1st minute, Josh Kennedy took a mark and kicked a goal to begin closing the gap.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney would take two marks full forward and kick goals as a result, closing the gap to just one point: Kieren Jack near the 5th minute and Jarrad McVeigh in the 6th minute.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney finally took the lead halfway through the quarter on a rapid drive down the middle of the ground finished by a kick by Sam Reid from the forward 50.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn finally had a shot on goal at the 13th minute from a David Hale mark, but it missed left.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney's Mitch Morton then kicked consecutive goals at the 14th and 16th minutes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn had two last shots in the closing two minutes, but both Franklin and Clinton Young kicked out on the full to the right.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney dominated the quarter with six goals to Hawthorn's lone behind, going from a 19-point deficit to a 16-point lead at half time.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn's Jarryd Roughead opened the quarter with a set shot missing to the left.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Between spells of back-and-forth play, Sydney managed to make two more goals from set shots: Kennedy in the 3rd minute, then Roberts-Thomson in the 6th minute.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Kennedy almost had another in the 8th minute but hit the post to extend the margin to 28: the largest at any point in the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Then Hawthorn started a 5.2 comeback: goals from David Hale, Franklin (2) Gunston, and Isaac Smith and behinds from Franklin and Matt Suckling (rushed) took them to a four-point lead.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] At this point, Hawthorn took out Xavier Ellis to bring in substitute Shane Savage.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] However, a crucial moment in the 18th minute in which Sam Mitchell gave away a 50-metre penalty saw Sydney captain McVeigh kick the resultant goal to regain the lead for Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Roughead crumbed one final shot at goal but hit the post, cutting Sydney's lead to just one point going into the final break.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Within one minute, Breust kicked his second goal, followed by another from Hale one minute later and a Franklin behind to give Hawthorn the lead by 12.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] After trading behinds with Hawthorn, Sydney finally substituted out Shane Mumford for Luke Parker, and they found opportunities with a goal from Dan Hannebery at the 9th minute.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Hodge's cut re-opened, forcing him off the field for several crucial minutes while they tried to bandage it.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] After several more back-and-forth minutes, Jack finally leveled the scores at 78 each with his second goal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] After Sydney forced a rushed behind to take a one-point lead, they stretched the lead to seven with a crumbing goal by Adam Goodes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn then pressed a lengthy attack in the forward 50 but could not convert on three opportunities: Gunston hit the post while two quick kicks from Brad Sewell went wide; they would only cut the lead to four.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Finally, Sydney cleared the ball and pressed their own attack.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] With less than 40 seconds left, Nick Malceski snapped the clinching goal from a pack in Sydney's forward line: the final score of the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn made a determined effort to come back, but Sydney played physically to deny them progress, keeping the ball at center square until the final siren.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The match in aggregate was a very even affair, with both sides dominating large passages of play.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] There is contention in who played better on the day, with Hawthorn missing key opportunities and registering more scoring shots.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Despite this, It is generally agreed that Sydney performed at key points in the game, including the last 10 minutes, with goals to Adam Goodes and Nick Malceski effectively sealing the game for Sydney.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Overall, the game was called as one of the best in modern times by Bruce McAvaney and Dennis Cometti, who were commentating on the day, for its sportsmanship and contest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Four members of the Sydney Swans' 2005 premiership team – Jude Bolton, Adam Goodes, Ryan O'Keefe and Lewis Roberts-Thomson – joined Vic Belcher as the only dual South Melbourne/Sydney Swans premiership players with the victory.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The Norm Smith Medal was won by Sydney's Ryan O'Keefe, who had 28 disposals and 15 tackles for the match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] O'Keefe polled 12 out of a maximum possible 15 votes for the award.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Ryan O'Keefe became the first man in South Melbourne/Sydney Swans history to win the Norm Smith Medal, making him one of the club's most decorated players in history with two premierships and a Norm Smith Medal.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Hawthorn's Brad Sewell finished second, with seven votes.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Sydney's Dan Hannebery and Hawthorn's Lance Franklin both polled five votes and Sydney captain Jarrad McVeigh polled one vote.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] The umpiring panel for the grand final comprised nine match day umpires and three emergencies.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Among the umpires were four grand final debutants: field umpires Matt Stevic and Simon Meredith, boundary umpire Rob Haala and goal umpire Chelsea Roffey.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/2012-afl-grand-final] Roffey became the first woman to officiate in an AFL grand final.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The sport was first introduced in 1905 in Vancouver, and despite tours involving American and Australian sides in 1912 and 1913, the sport went into permanent recess before World War I as a result of Australia's refusal to recognise Canada as a playing nation.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Three-quarters of a century later, the then VFL (now Australian Football League), having briefly gained then lost lucrative North American television broadcasts in the 1980s, attempted to rebuild its audience with a series of exhibition matches between 1987 and 1989.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] These matches generated significant interest and Canada retains the attendance record for the sport outside of Australia, 32,789 set in 1987 at B.C.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] As a result of the interest generated the sport was established at the grassroots in 1989 with a competition in Toronto that has continued and expanded to the present.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Competition spread from Ontario to other provinces culminating in the establishment of a national governing body, AFL Canada, in 2004.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The world governing body, the AFL Commission has recently made great efforts to differentiate it from rugby, producing educational videos such as "What is AFL?" aimed at a North American audience (Video on YouTube).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada has hosted the 49th Parallel Cup in 2000 and 2004 (in Toronto), 2007 (Vancouver), 2010 (Toronto), 2013 (Edomonton) and 2022 (Toronto) as well as the 2024 Transatlantic Cup in Toronto.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] It is home to the only dedicated Australian rules football ground in North America, the Humber College Oval at Colonel Samuel Smith Park in Toronto.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canadians are increasingly being sought after to play the sport professionally in Australia which has helped to increase overall interest in Canada.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Mike Pyke (who successfully switched from international rugby in 2008) featured prominently in red and white during his successful 2012 AFL Grand Final appearance, performing a victory lap with the Canadian flag.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Pyke has inspired others to follow and in 2016, Canadians featured prominently in AFL and AFL Women's recruitment with Andrew McGrath being taken as the top pick in the 2016 AFL draft and rugby convert Kendra Heil being picked in the 2016 AFL Women's draft.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada's best international results were posted in the 2014 International Cup with men's team, the Northwind, reaching 5th and the women's team, the Northern Lights, being crowned international champions.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] A request for copies of the Laws of Australian Football by parties from Canada was noted in the Sydney Referee newspaper in 1904.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] A 1906 report of Australian Football's growth internationally made mention of a Canadian Railway Commissioner early in the century who, while working in Victoria, fell in love with the sport and upon returning to Canada began agitating for it to be played there.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] He was said to have made several subsequent requests to parties in Australia for support introducing the game.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The game is believed to have been first introduced to British Columbia in 1905, when Canadian-born Captain Robert Nelson Davy of the 6th Regiment began training students of the 101st Canadian Cadet corps in preparation for a planned visit to Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The students were from the Vancouver School Board district and included the Vancouver High School Cadet Corps and King Edward High School among others.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However, by 1906 the game's newly formed governing body, the Australasian Football Council (AFC) led by the VFL resolved not to support the game being played outside Australasia and declined any support.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] West Australian Football League secretary John J Simons however pledged his support through the Young Australia League and began assisting to plan a series of tours between the two countries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Americans had come to Vancouver to help prepare Davy's cadets to compete against a touring Young Australia League from Perth scheduled to arrive that year and ultimately to tour Australia as Canada's first national team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] They played the first international match between the two countries in 1912 though few if any details of the match survive.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] A Young Australia League touring party left for Canada from the United States in January 1912.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However the West Australians were determined instead that Australian rules be played.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The result was that the AFC, led by the VFL withdrew all support for the tour, vowing to ensure that it was not a success.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Following the Young Australian tour the Canadian Cadets team prepared a reciprocal tour of Australia to Sydney, Perth, Fremantle, Kalgoorlie, Adelaide, Ballarat, Tasmania and Melbourne. $11,000 was raised for the tour with a contingent of 60 cadets aged 18 to 20.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadians left from Vancouver on July 10, 1912.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadian Cadets tour was plagued with trouble from the start.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Captain Davy had hoped that Australia would extend a similar reception to the one offered the 1909 American Schoolboys team and had intended to play numerous matches across Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However, the team was left in the lurch when the AFC refused to recognise the touring party which was not affiliated to it and officially declined participation from Australia's two most powerful leagues, the Victorian Football League and the South Australian Football Association.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Like the American tour, it was supported only by Western Australia's Young Australia League and the New South Wales Football Association (NSWAFA).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Nash president of the NSWAFA saw it as an opportunity to promote the idea that the game was spreading abroad.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] This was something that the NSWAFA in particular believed was important to appeal to the Sydney public which had gained enormous interest in representative rugby.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The NSWAFA had invested heavily in a thriving schoolboys competition and sending Sydney schoolboy Eric Cullen-Ward to North America had successfully kick-started the code beyond the league's expectations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The AFC led by the VFL however were convinced that the key to converting Sydneysiders was through its promotion of national competition and as a truly national football code featuring its VFL clubs.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Much to the chagrin of the touring Canadians and the NSWAFA, the AFC and VFL scheduled a clashing fixture, featuring the Geelong Football Club against the New South Wales state team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However the AFC's exhibition match move backfired and the Queensland vs New South Wales rugby match being played that week dominated Sydney's media attention.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadian tour, swept up in anti-VFL sentiment, was afforded the barest of mentions by the media.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canadian tour manager E.R McTaggart made an advanced visit to promote the match only to have the matches postponed due to Australian organisers difficulties scheduling the tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Cadets arrived on HMS Zealandia in Sydney on August 4.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Organisers claimed that the abuse was so bad that at one point the touring party, mostly self-funded, considered returning home.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Captain Davy commented that "the people of Canada won't understand this treatment.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] They will wonder if there is any thing wrong with the boys or with me.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] We treated the Australian boys who visited us in a very different fashion".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Adding insult to injury the NSWAFA public statement on behalf of the Sydney public placed the blame on the Australasian Football Council and the visiting Canadians.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Despite the NSWAFA's "apology" the Government of New South Wales offered a formal apology and refunded the expenses while visiting the state.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Officials from Newcastle and Goulburn made a concerted effort to atone for Sydney's hostile reception for the scheduled visits however the matches were abandoned due to state of the football grounds.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Sydney matches themselves were low key events, and were rescheduled several times during and there was much difficulty securing grounds to play from rugby authorities.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Reportedly skills, particularly bouncing the ball, let the touring side down, though they were competitive against the Australians.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In contrast to the New South Wales tour, the cadets received a parade in Melbourne and a full page welcoming in The Argus.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However they faced a stern lack of support from Victorian football authorities, the cadets who had trained to play in the home of football, instead competed and lost in other sports including lacrosse at the Melbourne Cricket Ground.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] A rare exception was during the visit to Newport a local amateur team agreed to play an unsanctioned match and were completely shocked to have been soundly beaten by the visitors.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadians went on to Western Australia where they were greeted with much fanfare and were hosted by the WAFL (who had sponsored the Young Australia League) where they would play several matches and with the experience gathered on the tour, displayed much improved performance.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In Perth, the West Australian Football League organised a match featuring the Young Australia League Matches in West Australia drew by far the largest attendances of the Australian tour.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Following the North American tour from and to Australia, the AFC demanded that the West Australian Football Association stop all of its financial subsidies of international football, which it did in 1913.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] There were reports that despite the failed tour the sport continued to be played in the high schools at least until the war though the Vancouver Board began increasingly playing rugby after the successful 1912 Vancouver rugby tour against Stanford Rugby in the United States.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] A proposal was debated by the Australasian Football Council in 1915 of a tour to Canada, with a decision deferred until after the war.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada was never granted membership to the council and the game appears to have died out there during World War I.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In the late 1980s, TSN broadcasts in Canada showed highlights of the Victorian Football League from Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] However the league's once lucrative North American broadcast rights dried up and in response it initiated a series of exhibition matches between 1987 and 1989 in an attempt to rebuild its audience.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The first major exhibition matches in Canada attracted three of the largest crowds for the sport in the world, along with much interest.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The 1987 game holds the record for a VFL/AFL match held outside Australia.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadian Australian Football Association was established in May 1989 when two clubs, the Mississauga Mustangs and the Toronto Panthers were formed and played in the inaugural Conacher Cup game in Toronto, Ontario.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Since then, the game of Australian football in Canada has expanded considerably nationwide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 1990, the Scarborough Rebels, the North York Hawks and the Hamilton Wildcats joined, with the Balmy Beach Saints coming on board in 1992.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The North York Hawks later relocated and became known as the Broadview Hawks.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Brampton Wolverines, the league's seventh team, were formed in 1993.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Scarborough Rebels relocated and became the Lawrence Park Rebels.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 1993, a Canadian representative team, known as the Northwind, beat a British (BARFL) representative team.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 1994 and 1995, the Canadians again defeated the British at home.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 1995, several local CAFA games were broadcast on a Hamilton cable television channel.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In July 1995, the Hamilton Wildcats played a Canadian All-Star team in front of 21,000 fans during the half-time break at a Canadian Football League (gridiron) match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 1999, the first USA v Canada game was played (49th Parallel Cup, named after the 49th parallel north).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Revolution narrowly defeated Team Canada (Northwind).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Later matches enforced strict rules based on player origins.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The 49th Parallel Cup is held every two years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2002, Canada participated in the inaugural Australian Football International Cup, with Canada represented by the Northwind team consisting purely of Canadian-born players.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The Canadian national team has competed in every International Cup since its inception and now competes with its national women's team named the Northern Lights.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2003, the first junior league in Canada, the North Delta Junior Australian Football League, was formed.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] AFL Canada was formed as governing body on 30 July 2004, when the Canadian Australian Football League changed its official name.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The move corresponded with funding from the Australian Football League, and a junior participation program was put in place.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The clubs were split into two regional leagues, the Ontario Australian Football League and the North West Pacific Football League.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The remaining Alberta-based clubs participate in AFL Canada organised regional conferences such as the British Columbia Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2005, the Northwind participated in the 2005 International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In early 2006, AFL Canada sent a small delegation to the AFL exhibition match in Los Angeles.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] London and Windsor folded due to distance but the new OAFL club, the Central Blues, formed and began competing.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In Alberta, the Calgary Bears also formed and the Westcoast challenge commenced.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In early 2007, the Ottawa Swans formed, and affiliated with the OAFL, and the Demons relocated from Mississauga to High Park in Toronto.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In late 2007, AFL Canada hosted the Ironbark challenge, including the 49th Parallel Cup between Canada vs United States, including historic first women's and junior (under 17) tests between the two countries.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada defeated the United States for the first time at both senior and junior level, but were soundly defeated in the women's match.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The tournament also included a touring Japanese team and attracted a record attendance of 2,500 at Thunderbird Stadium in Vancouver.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Several professional and international players have strong connections to Canada.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In early 2008, junior Northwind representative Scott Fleming moved to Australia to play with the Broadbeach Cats semi-professional club in the AFL Queensland State League at 17 years of age.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Later the same year, former Canadian rugby union international Mike Pyke was signed by the Sydney Swans AFL team as an international rookie at 24 years of age.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Andrew McGrath, who was born in Canada, was drafted first overall in the 2016 AFL draft by Essendon.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Kendra Heil signed with Collingwood of AFL Women's in 2017.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The governing body for Aussie Rules in Canada is AFL Canada.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Team Canada for men is known as the Northwind.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Team Canada for women is known as the Northern Lights.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2019, there were a total of 875 registered senior players in organised competitions across 41 clubs with more than 20,000 junior registrations.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Participation has more than doubled since 2006, when there were over 420 senior (approximately 250 Canadian national) Australian rules football players in Canada out of a total of 484, an increase of 25% from 2005.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] By the end of 2007, this figure had increased to a total of 825 players in organised competitions across 21 clubs, of which 525 were senior and 300 were junior, an increase of over 70% from 2006, and a total of 95% increase over 2 years.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada boasts 9 women's football clubs nationwide.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Youth girls development programs operate in Alberta, British Columbia, Ontario and Quebec.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] The national team, formed in 2007, is known as the "Northern Lights".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] They were formerly known as the "Eagles".
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] They played in the first women's international footy matches during 2007, when they lost twice to the USA Freedom.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2011 the national women's team competed in the inaugural women's division of the Australian Football International Cup, where they came second to Ireland.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2014 the Northern lights became world champions when they defeated the Irish Banshees at the AFL International Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2015 the Northern Lights defeated the USA Freedom to win the annual 49th Parallel Cup.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] TV coverage of the AFL in Canada has historically included the weekly highlights program going back to the 1980s.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In the mid-1990s when ESPN briefly reacquired the rights to the AFL in US again (due to lobbying by fans associated with AFANA), the sport first appeared on The Sports Network, better known as TSN.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In succeeding years, the sport moved between several networks but was primarily on TSN.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Coverage remained limited to highlights programs save for one time each year, where the Grand Final (championship game) was usually live.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2006, due to growing demand and lobbying by AFANA for regular live coverage, the new Setanta Sports acquired rights in both Canada and the USA.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In mid-season that year, live matches began appearing regularly on television in Canada for the first time on Setanta Sports (STS).
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] When Setanta's North American operations failed in August 2010, the sport briefly moved to Rogers Sportsnet.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Following ESPN winning the rights once again in the US, the sport returned to TSN, where it remains.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] TSN now airs one live match and one delayed match each round of the AFL season, both available in HD.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] For many years, fans in extreme western Canada have been able to see coverage via mid-size or large satellite dishes able to catch signals low on the horizon intended for the Pacific via first Australia TV and now by its successor Australia Plus.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] AFANA provides listings of Canadian TV schedules on its web site along with information on the coverage.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] In 2011, the first televised all-Canadian Aussie Rules match was shown on Rogers TV, and featured the Ottawa Swans hosting the Toronto Rebels.
[src:australian-rules-football-in-canada/australian-rules-football-in-canada] Canada holds the world record for attendance at a match outside Australia.
